    <title>Combined summary - BIP174 extension proposal (Global Type: PSBT_GLOBAL_XPUB_SIGNATURE)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T19:40:54.577589+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-June/017047.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email thread discussed proposals to extend the Partially Signed Bitcoin Transaction (PSBT) scheme. One proposal suggests dealing with PSBT metainformation outside of PSBT or using vendor/metainformation-specific fields to prevent the core specification from growing too big. Another proposal aims to add functionality for verifying that the recipient address is not fraudulent, providing an extra layer of security for cold-to-warm and warm-to-hot wallet transactions. Two formats are suggested - one for normal cases and another for serial numbered packages requiring different versions of xpub packages signed by certain cold keys. Concerns were raised about how the scheme handles multisig as attackers could potentially create a single-sig destination address they control and move coins in a chain of two transactions if individual xpubs were signed with cold keys.To address this issue, Jonathan Underwood suggested requiring m=1 for single-sig cases and using 0 as an indicator for a serial number following it. However, it was noted that 0x00 is already used for single sig or OP_CHECKSIG, while 0x01 is used for multisig or 1-of-3, 1-of-2 OP_CHECKMULTISIG.Overall, the conversations highlight the importance of creating a more secure environment for HD wallets and the need for a standardized solution that can be adopted by various hardware wallets. Feedback on the proposals is being welcomed.</summary>
